### 1. The "Smoking Gun": C++26 Features
The most precise temporal marker in the text is the section on **Language evolution**:
> "Looking forward, **C++26** will likely have stackful coroutines, the ability to embed binary file contents to initialize arrays, a safe range-based for loop..."

*   **Context:** The ISO C++ standardization process works on a 3-year cycle. C++20 was released in late 2020. C++23 was released in late 2023. C++26 is the next major standard.
*   **Timeline:** For an author to confidently list specific features *expected* in C++26 (like stackful coroutines and binary literals in arrays) as "likely" but not yet "standard," the text must be written **after** the feature proposals for C++26 had been discussed and gained traction in the committee, but **before** the standard was finalized.
*   **Specifics:**
    *   **Stackful Coroutines:** This was a major topic of debate in the C++ committee around 2023–2024. The specific phrasing suggests the author is looking at the *proposal* stage.
    *   **Binary File Contents:** This refers to proposals like P1907 (or similar) regarding embedding resources, which were active discussions in the 2023–2024 timeframe.
    *   **Safe range-based for loop:** This likely refers to proposals regarding bounds checking or iterator safety (e.g., P2642 or similar discussions) that were gaining momentum.
*   **Deduction:** If the text treats C++26 as a future standard with specific features "likely" to be included, it was written **after the C++23 release (late 2023)** and **before the C++26 standard was finalized (late 2025)**. The specificity suggests it is likely **mid-to-late 2024**, when the feature set for C++26 was being solidified.

